/*!
  \page install_docker Build PandA framework in container environment
  The repository ships container recipes that can be used to build and test PandA in a reproducible Linux environment.
  This page intentionally stays at a high level: container layouts, image tags, and helper scripts evolve more often than the Doxygen pages.

  \section install_docker_req Prerequisites
  Install a recent Docker engine on the host system and make sure the current user can run container commands.

  \section install_docker_overview Container files in the repository
  Container-related assets live in the repository itself:
  - \c .devcontainer/Dockerfile
  - \c .devcontainer/Dockerfile.yosys
  - helper scripts under \c .devcontainer/library-scripts/

  These files are the authoritative source for the container environment. When in doubt, prefer the checked-in Dockerfiles and scripts over older prose documentation.

  \section install_docker_usage Recommended workflow
  A conservative container workflow is:
  - build the image from the Dockerfile that matches your use case;
  - mount the repository into the container;
  - run the normal project build from inside the container, preferring the CMake flow documented for the repository;
  - install the built tree before invoking \c bambu, so the executable uses the matching installed plugins and libraries.

  This approach avoids coupling the documentation to a specific wrapper command or compose file.

  \section install_docker_notes Notes
  The container environment is mainly useful to:
  - reproduce builds on a known Linux userspace;
  - isolate host-specific package differences;
  - prepare AppImage or toolchain-oriented build setups without polluting the host machine.

  If you need to customize the environment, edit the Dockerfiles or helper scripts under \c .devcontainer/ and keep any command examples aligned with those files.

  
  \section install_docker_next Next steps
  - \ref bambu101_page
  - \ref dev_page


*/
